PLAGUE, FATAL - ECUADOR (CHIMBORAZO) (02)
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>


[1]
Date: Tue, 11 May 2004
From: Renato Leon <renatol@mail.usfq.edu.ec>
Source:This information is derived from 2 articles published in El Universo
newspaper, 11 May 2004.
<http://www.eluniverso.com/core/12/eluniverso.asp?page=noticia&id=12&tab=1&contid=42873F9E44A34017B29E58A990A5ED0E&EUID=>


According to an Ecuadorian newspaper, the health department in Chimborazo
Province (located in the Andean mountains) advised local medical personnel
that patients admitted from the town of Guamote presenting fever, cough,
enlargement of the lymph nodes, weakness and malaise, should be considered
as suspected cases of bubonic plague. This decision was taken after
confirming 3 fatal cases due to the disease in the last 2 months.

The death of several guinea pigs (cuyes) has been reported in the
community of San Pedro de Yaucupamba, where 2 human fatalities have already
occurred. Unfortunately, the information was suppressed, said Dr. Adela
Vimos, Director of Epidemiology, Chimborazo Province. It also mentioned
that personnel from the Malaria Control Program are currently spraying in
the community of San Pedro de Yaucupamba, the urban area of Guamote and
other vicinity communities including Santa Teresita, Cochaloma and
Jatumpamba. Teachers from local schools started an educational campaign to
prevent the occurrence of new cases.

According to Vimos, the disease is endemic in the region, reason why the
new re-emergence of human cases is a dangerous threat to the community
health. The health authorities of the Province of Chimborazo have also
prohibited the consumption of guinea pigs and rabbits in the region until
the transmission of the disease is controlled. The manipulation of flesh,
consumption of poorly cooked guinea pigs, or the direct contact with the
host or the infected fleas could potentially lead to human infection -- all
reasons that the health authorities urge the elimination of guinea pigs,
rabbits, and rats, especially in the areas from where the cases were
reported.

--
Renato Leon Ph.D.
Universidad San Francisco de Quito
Quito, Ecuador
<renatol@mail.usfq.edu.ec>

******
[2]
Date: Mon, 10 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Universo.com, Ecuador, 10 (05/2004) [translated by Maria Jacobs,
ProMED-ESP; edited]
<http://www.eluniverso.com/core/eluniverso.asp?edicion=1&page=noticia&id=12&tab=1&contid=7AD620E20FAD4796924EEE07F93EACC5>


The health authorities of Chimborazo confirmed that over the past 2 months,
in the canton of Guamote, a mother and her daughter died with symptoms
compatible with bubonic plague. A 3rd person presenting similar symptoms is
hospitalized in the isolation unit of a teaching hospital in the city of
Riobamba.

The health authorities issued a ban on the consumption of cavies or guinea
pigs (_Cavia porcellus_), and rabbits due to a reappearance of bubonic plague.

Adela Vimos, head of Epidemiology of the Health Department of Chimborazo,
reported that in the canton of Guamote, and particularly in the community
of San Pedro de Yacupamba, the disease has been present for several years,
and that over the past few months a dangerous resurgence of the disease has
been observed.

The epidemiology department is carrying out control measures that include
the fumigation of high-risk areas. Vimos placed special emphasis on the
need to abstain from the commerce and consumption of cavies and rabbits.

--
