[3]
Date: Wed, 12 May 2004 20:33:41 -0400
To: promed@promedmail.org

From: Abramo Ottolenghi <ottolenghi.1@osu.edu>
Source: Summarized from El Comercio on line Quito 11 and 12 May 2004
<http://www.elcomercio.com/noticias.asp?noid=93313>
<http://www.elcomercio.com/noticias.asp?noid=93338>


A 55 year old woman and her 22 year old daughter died of bubonic plague in
the locality of Guamote in the province of Chimborazo. The mother and
daughter raised guinea pigs for sale. These animals are a common food in
the Andean region. 500 persons were treated to prevent spread of the
disease. The epidemiological focus was identified and according to
authorities an epidemiological containment circle has been
established. High risk areas will be fumigated to eradicate the fleas.

Authorities indicated that plague is endemic in that area (grasslands over
2000 mts. above sea level). When it rains rats that live in those
grasslands seek refuge in inhabited areas. In this case a rat bit a guinea
pig that was then consumed by the deceased. On April 29th an alert was
issued for the provinces of Cotopaxi, Tungurahua, Bol√≠var, Azuay and
Chimborazo. No new cases have been detected.

--
Abramo Ottolenghi, Ph.D.
